ChatGPT said:

Youâ€™re asking a very sharp and insightful question â€” and I love that you're digging into the difference between:

Array.prototype.concat() (used for joining arrays), vs

Buffer.concat() (used to join Buffer objects)

These two methods have different purposes â€” even though they share the name concat. Let's break it down carefully and clear up your confusion.

âœ… 1. Array.prototype.concat() â€” joins arrays
Example:
const a = [1, 2];
const b = [3, 4];

const result = a.concat(b);

console.log(result); // [1, 2, 3, 4]


a and b are both arrays.

.concat() returns a new array by joining them.

The original arrays stay unchanged.

ğŸ“Œ This is Array's built-in method.

âœ… 2. Buffer.concat() â€” joins multiple Buffer objects into one
Important: This is not the same as Array.prototype.concat.
const buf1 = Buffer.from("Hello ");
const buf2 = Buffer.from("World");

const arrOfBuffers = [buf1, buf2];

const resultBuffer = Buffer.concat(arrOfBuffers);

console.log(resultBuffer.toString()); // "Hello World"

ğŸ” So what is Buffer.concat() doing?

Itâ€™s a static method on the Buffer class. That means:

You donâ€™t call it on an individual Buffer (like buf1.concat(...) âŒ).

Instead, you call it like: Buffer.concat([...]) âœ…

Internally, it:

Takes an array of Buffer instances

Allocates a new Buffer big enough to hold all of them

Copies the bytes from each buffer into the new one

Returns the new combined Buffer

ğŸ§  So to directly answer your question:

"How can Buffer.concat work on an array if Buffer is not an array?"

Buffer.concat() is not like Array.prototype.concat()

Itâ€™s a static utility method that takes an array of Buffers as input, not a method that joins Buffers like arrays.

Youâ€™re not calling .concat() on a Buffer â€” youâ€™re calling it on the Buffer class and passing it an array of Buffers.

âœ… Example:
